Scientists have found a way to detect related stars
Astrophysics from the University of California in Santa Cruz studied turbulence and its impact on chemical homogeneity in star clusters.
It is expected that the discovery of experts will allow for the search of related stars, i.e. those originating from the same cluster.
The results of their research were published in Nature magazine and are briefly available on the university's website.
The cause of the same chemical composition of nearby stars is the turbulence in the clouds of gas prior to the formation of stars.
Even if the born star then leaves the stellar cluster, its chemical composition can determine the place of its birth and the region of formation of the descendant stars.
Scientists have previously had doubts that the evolution of a star outside the cluster may result in differences in its chemical content from those of relatives in the cluster.
Modelling results from astrophysics show that such differences should not appear.
In their study, experts using a supercomputer modeled two streams of interstellar gas that together formed a cloud.
This object has been transformed for several million years by its own gravity into a cluster in which protostars begin to form.
Scientists added markings to the initial gas streams and found that rapid turbulence in the cloud resulted in a high degree of chemical uniformity.
Astrophysics is believed by its researchers to prove that it is possible to search for chemically related stars as well as to identify possible regions of the formation of such objects.
