Remembering the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis proposed a bill under which the organization of trade unions is protected as civil law.
"Where unions are, there are middle-class jobs," says Allison, a Minnesota Democrat who is co-chair of Congress Progressive Fraction.
That's why I'm proud to present the Workers Empowerment Act along with the symbol of the civil rights movement John Lewis.
This innovative bill will give workers the same legal opportunity to discriminate against trade union organizations as other forms of discrimination by stopping the forces of trade union opponents.
The amendment of the Labour Relations Regulation Act to allow workers who face discrimination for participating in trade union organizations to seek justice in the civil courts - and to receive damages and fines - a reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to figure out what Allison, Lewis, and the co-authors of the bill are to remember a very American thought.
Despite the attacks that trade unions have suffered in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country - Americans once supported countries around the world in accepting, expanding and respecting labour rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remembered when that country simultaneously defended democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas McArthur and his aides helped the country adopt a constitution drafted to guarantee that Hideki Tojo's paramilitary autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions played a role in shaping the new Japan, they included a text that explicitly recognized that “the right of workers to organize, to negotiate and to collective action is guaranteed”.
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhauser and his assistants helped the Germans to write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers would need to be organized and heard in the new State, the Germans included an article that stated openly: “The right to form associations to protect and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to infringe this right will have no legal effect; measures to that end will be declared illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was Chairman of the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the World Declaration on Human Rights to be adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a world agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that “everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions to protect his interests”.
For generations, Americans have taken for granted the basic position that labour rights are human rights.
When that country consulted other countries on how to build civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to organize trade unions - and to have that trade union participate as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - should be protected.
Now that these rights are being attacked in America, it is wise indeed to return to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement did not undermine the nation's power, but increased it.
By raising the standard of living of millions, trade unions miraculously created a market for industry and raised an entire nation to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack trade unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how it owes us.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination against the organization of trade unions - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive the ideals that historically expanded America and made the promise of democracy a reality.
The judge temporarily blocks a law that could close all abortion clinics in Louisiana.
In the United States, a federal judge temporarily blocked the enactment of Louisiana law on Sunday, about which his supporters say he will likely close all five abortion clinics in the state.
Under this measure, which was signed for execution by Louisiana Governor Bobby Jinadl in June and was due to enter into force on September 1, doctors who perform abortions would be required to have authority to receive patients in the hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge ' s decision meant that doctors could now continue to perform legal abortions while continuing to seek such authority.
"The plaintiffs will be allowed to work legally while continuing to take action to obtain authority," wrote Judge John de Gravels in his decision.
A hearing will be scheduled within a month during which the judge will render a more permanent decision on the law.
Advocates of the right to abortion welcomed this decision, the latest in a series of decisions against similar measures, saying that it would give doctors more time to obtain hospital authority.
"Today's decision guarantees that Louisiana women will be protected from a treacherous law that seeks to deprive them of their health and rights," said Nancy Northapp, president and head of the Center for Reproductive Rights, who filed a lawsuit to stop the law on behalf of three of the five state clinics.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision applied to doctors from the two clinics who had not filed claims in the case and also applied for admission.
Louisiana is in 11 states that have passed such laws, and the courts have recently ruled such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key parts of the Texas law, which would close most of the remaining clinics in this state, were blocked by a federal judge on Friday.
Lawyers for the right to abortion, together with the American College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists and the American Medical Association, say that laws on admission powers impose restrictions on doctors that are not medically necessary.
Opponents of abortion argue that such measures are aimed at protecting women ' s health, although some also noted their positive effect in closing clinics.
Only one doctor who aborts in Louisiana has the authority to receive at the hospital, reported to the Center for Reproductive Rights.
If all other doctors in the state were forced to stop doing this, the doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop doing so, the team reported.
Criticizing this decision, Louisiana officials said they would not punish abortion doctors while their applications for admission were awaiting a decision.
