Untimely diagnosed and lack of access to optimal treatment means that ovarian cancer in rural areas kills more
Angelina Jolie and her brother James published a video of the memory of their late mother, who died of ovarian cancer in 2007.
Women who forgive in rural Australia face a higher risk of death from ovarian cancer than those living in urban areas.
Researchers analysed the disease maps of more than 1,100 Australian women diagnosed with ovarian cancer in 2005, finding that only 35 per cent had lived five years after being diagnosed.
Senior researcher Susan Jordan of the QIMR Berghofer Institute of Medical Research reported that the probability of dying during the study is 20 percent higher for those living in regions and remote areas of the state than for those living in urban areas.
A LOT RESEARCH: New drugs can slow down lung cancer and ovarian cancer
Researchers followed the medical path of women in seven years.
Dr. Jordan said that the woman's age at the time of diagnosis, the type of ovarian cancer, the presence of current diseases and socio-economic status also affected the likelihood of survival.
Older women and those who had cancer at a later stage at the time of diagnosis had the lowest survival rates.
For those living in regions or remote areas of the state, the probability of dying during the study was 20 per cent higher than for those living in urban areas.
Although the study was not designed to determine why women living outside cities were more likely to die from ovarian cancer, Dr. Jordan suggested that delayed diagnosis and lack of access to optimal treatment were possible factors.
"This disease is best treated by surgeons specializing in gynaecology cancer, and they are mostly in big cities," she said.
Despite improving the quality of tele-health services to reduce the impact of distance, she suggested that an increase in the number of exit services that would allow professionals to treat women closer to home, and programmes to support people undergoing treatment far away from their home, could help.
Dr. Jordan said that regardless of geographical location, the study revealed that the long life expectancy of women with ovarian cancer was rare, stressing the need for more effective treatment and prevention strategies.
The study, funded by Rio Tinto Ride to Conquer cancer, will be published today in the Medical Journal of Australia.
