Genetic disorder is often misdiagnosed
Britain reported that she had spent many years thinking she was going to die after having been misdiagnosed.
Karen Rogers spent most of his teenage age thinking she had only a few years to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
In fact, she had Charco-Marie-Tout's disease (SMT), a group of hereditary disorders that result in nerve damage outside the brain and spine.
CMT UK's charity reported that misdiagnosis is a frequent problem among people with SMTs because so little is known about this condition.
Some 23,000 people in the UK are believed to have a CMT that can cause motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, insecure walking, and strained toes.
Patients may feel numbness or pain, and the condition is not cured and progressing, meaning that symptoms increase over time.
When Rogers was 13, she thought she was suffering from Friedreich's (AF) attack, a condition for which the prognosis was very bad.
Rogers thought she'd be chained to a wheelchair by the time she was 18, and die before she was 30.
The mother of the two children now 51 said, "As a child, I knew I couldn't do what others did.
I fell every day, and it took me longer.
I could never skate or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied a lot at school because of the way I went and ran.
Rogers said that when she was 13, after several surgeries to release the Ahill tendon and straighten her feet, she looked into the medical records when her doctor left the room, and it said she had an AF.
