The tax burden on Washington zone entrepreneurs increases as the economy recovers
A recovering economy means more customers, more sales, and new jobs.
This also means higher taxes.
State and local tax bills for companies across the country increased moderately last year when economic recovery accelerated, according to a new study published last week, and a company in the Washington Zone is no exception.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia paid $27.6 billion together to the state and local treasury in fiscal year 2013, 3.8 per cent more than the $26.6 billion collected in 2012.
The tax burden on state and local businesses increased by 4.3 per cent last year, to $671 billion, from 3.9 per cent a year earlier, and this was the third consecutive year of growth after successive years when accounts declined, in 2009 and 2010.
State taxes increased faster, 4.3 per cent than local taxes, 3.9 per cent, according to a study conducted by a professional service firm, Ernst & Young, and the State Tax Center, a tax policy group.
More than half of the district's tax revenue, 56 per cent, comes from entrepreneurs, while 36 per cent of Maryland's tax revenue comes from firms.
Virginia, with 28 per cent, has the lowest tax revenue, proportionally, from entrepreneurs.
Much of the increase in tax revenues is due to a return to the old value of companies' real estate, researchers say, which raised real estate taxes by 3.7 per cent this year after three consecutive years of growth of less than 1 per cent.
While large states such as California, New York, and Texas account for a large proportion of these revenues, the same seems to be happening in the Washington Zone.
Companies in the county, Maryland and Virginia paid $10 billion in state and local real estate taxes last year, $9.6 billion more than in 2012, a 4.2 per cent increase over the previous year.
However, the observed return on real estate does not have any similar effect on the increase in state and local tax revenues in Maryland, where real estate taxes barely exceed one fifth of companies' tax accounts.
Virginia and D.C. companies pay about half of state and local tax bills in the form of real estate taxes.
"What happens in Maryland is that such a large part of their real estate, especially the tax base around Columbia County, is owned either by the government or by a non-profit organization that does not pay real estate taxes," said Douglas Lindholm, executive director of the State Tax Center.
Thus, Maryland has to rely much more on, for example, income taxes to pay for the same services as in other states.
The recent increase in tax revenues from entrepreneurs cannot be fully attributed to the re-establishment of the real estate market.
The income of entrepreneurs also seems to be on the right track, according to these data.
Companies in the region declared a $2.3 billion state-level corporate income tax, $2.1 billion more than in 2012.
Maryland collected $1 billion of corporate income tax revenue, the largest in the region.
While trends are in the same direction, the tax burden of entrepreneurs at the local level is not increasing at the same rate in all three locations.
The growth rate in the District of Columbia was the same as the national average of 4.3 per cent, while the growth rate in Maryland was significantly faster, 4.9 per cent.
In Virginia alone, tax revenues rose below an average of 4.1 per cent.
Virginia had the lowest corporate income tax of three jurisdictions (each with the same corporate rate) at 6 per cent.
In Maryland, the corporate rate is 8.25 per cent, compared with a relatively high rate of 9.975 per cent in the county.
A similar study by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce earlier this year showed that Virginia lower taxes for state and local entrepreneurs and, in general, a more favourable climate for taxes for entrepreneurs than Maryland.
The county was not assessed in this study.
Despite its advantage, Virginia is under competitive pressure from her neighbour from the south.
North Carolina has recently signed legislation reducing the corporate rate this year from 6.9 per cent to 6 per cent, as in Virginia, and the rate will drop to 5 per cent next year.
If the state continues to achieve its tax revenue targets next year, this law could bring the income tax rate for entrepreneurs even to 3 per cent by 2017.
Meanwhile, small businesses in the Washington Zone seem to feel better and thus pay more state and local taxes, according to a recent study.
Taxes on entrepreneurs paid in the form of an individual income tax by small business owners - a transition structure that accommodates most small firms - in the District of Columbia, Maryland and Virginia increased by 20 per cent last year to $2.4 billion, at a much higher rate of growth than taxes for entrepreneurs in general.
Researchers say that the trend and increase in business tax revenue across the country is likely to continue this year, with turnover tax revenues in state and local governments increasing by 6.2 per cent in the first three quarters of 2014 compared to the same period last year.
However, the Washington Zone may lag behind, as lower federal spending affects the labour market in the region.
