Deputies suggested speeding up the entry into force of the Personal Data Act
If the initiative succeeds, Russians will not be able to store data on servers abroad as of 1 January 2015
A bill has been introduced in the State Duma to extend the date of entry into force of the already adopted Act on Personal Data of Russians, from 1 September 2016 to 1 January 2015.
The initiative is located in the lower house legislative framework.
It was sponsored by members of the State Duma, Vadim Mánn, Yaroslav Nilov (LDPR), Evgeny Fedorov (Single Russia), Vladimir Parahin (Just Russia) and Alexander Yushchenko (KPRF).
Such a change would, in the view of the proponents, help to ensure the rights of citizens of the Russian Federation to protect personal data and to maintain the confidentiality of correspondence in information and telecommunications networks more quickly and effectively.
The Act, the entry into force of which is rushed by parliamentarians, requires Russians to keep their personal data on the territory of the Russian Federation processed via the Internet.
It also requires the recording, systematization, stockpiling, storage, refining and retrieval of the personal data of citizens of the Russian Federation in databases located on Russian territory, as well as the indication of the location of such databases.
In addition, the law gives Roscomnadzor the right to restrict access to information treated in violation of Russian personal data legislation by a court decision.
The Act also proposes the creation of so-called “blacklists” of violators' websites, an automated information system called “The Register of violators of the rights of personal data subjects”.
This law was passed by the State Duma in the summer.
The draft law was sponsored by Andrei Lugova and Vadim Dewyn of LDPR and Alexander Yushchenko of CRCF.
Moneyn and Yushchenko are also co-authors of the current bill on the postponement of the date of entry into force of the already adopted law.
Those who don't have a date center in the Russian Federation will have to pay rent.
Commenting on the bill introduced today in the State Duma, the first head of the Duma Information Policy Committee, Leonid Levine, stated that he saw no problem in relocating the date of entry into force of the Personal Data Protection Act.
According to him, those companies that by 1 January 2015 would not have their own personal data storage facilities for Russians on the territory of the Russian Federation would be able to lease them, for example, to the Rostelcom, which has repeatedly said that they are willing to lease their servers and already provide their servers, from the Mail Group, to Western companies that are already providing their servers today.
"In addition, there are several independent data centres ready to cooperate in this field," he added.
"If companies decide to comply with the law and continue to work on the territory of the Russian Federation, I see no problem - they will have technological accommodation," Levin summarized.
Controversial Bill
Immediately after the publication of the draft law, the Russian Electronic Communications Association feared that if the bill was adopted, Russians would no longer be able to use many global Internet services.
These include online airline booking and hotel services.
In the opinion of the association, “the draft law deprives the subjects of personal data - citizens of the Russian Federation - of the right to dispose of their own data by making it imperative that their recording, systematization, etc. should be ensured only in databases located in the territory of the Russian Federation”.
The RAEC statement emphasizes that a more effective measure would be to establish a mechanism to inform the user of where the recording is done and to systematize its personal data.
In such a case, it will be possible to choose the territory in which the acts will be carried out.
The adoption of similar bills on the “localization” of personal data in other countries has led to the departure of global services and significant economic losses.
