The angry expression of the face - the swirled and lowered eyebrows drawn into the thin line of lips, the bloated nostrils - is the same in all cultures, and makes it even the birthless children who never saw it, is noted by the lead author of the study Aaron Sell.
As part of a major research project on the nature of anger, scientists found that this emotion had arisen to effectively manage disputes during the conflict.
The more physical harm one person can do to another, the more he is able to dictate his conditions, and he communicates it to the interlocutor through anger.
Researchers have also found evidence of another hypothesis: physically strong people are more likely to get angry and to resort to physical abuse, consider themselves entitled to impose adverse conditions on others, and prefer violent methods of resolving conflicts peacefully.
Based on the fact that anger is primarily an “emotion of bargaining”, scientists have decided that the movements of each of the seven muscle groups that create the angry expression of the face must represent the angry individual more powerful and dangerous in the eyes of the interviewer - and thus force him to accept its terms as soon as possible in order to avoid conflict.
To test this hypothesis, researchers modeled on the computer faces where each of the seven elements of the angry face was present or missing, and showed them to the informants.
Although the lower eyebrows or the forward chin did not individually make the face angry, the more physically powerful pictured person was unanimously acknowledged by the study.
The anger of man, like that of animals, is a threat: an exaggerated exercise of self-power that compels consent and submission.
A man blowes his nostrils and presses his lips for the same purpose as a frog that inflates, or a baboon that shows his fangs.
“Anger is `launched' by the interlocutor's refusal to accept the situation, and the person immediately takes the form most effectively showing the opposite side the consequences of the refusal.
But most striking - that none of the components of the angry face is arbitrary, all of them express the same thing," said anthropologist John Toubi.
The Ministry of Communications has offered 250 million rubles to the Crimea television and radio company.
The Ministry of Communications has proposed that 250 million rubles be allocated from the federal budget in 2014 to the autonomous non-profit organization Crimea Teleradiocom Company.
This is mentioned in the draft government decree prepared by the agency consulted by Lenta.ru.
According to the Explanatory Note to the project, subsidies from the federal budget will be directed “to cover the costs of creating conditions for extensive informational coverage of the socio-economic situation and the development of a modern information space in the territory of the Republic of Crimea, including the acquisition of equipment”.
In particular, it is intended to convert the hardware and studio unit, the video walls, the central hardware and video server.
The acquisition of a mobile television station and a satellite transmitter is also planned.
In addition, the company will pay for the use of the fibre-optic link (VOLS) and the maintenance of the energy system from the funds allocated.
Grants will be provided within the federal budget of the Ministry of Communications.
The State Broadcasting Company Crimea was established in 1959 and broadcasts in seven languages: Ukrainian, Russian, Crimean Tatar, German, Greek, Bulgarian and Armenian.
To date, television coverage of the radio and television company is more than 75 per cent of the peninsula.
In 2011, Crimea Teleradio Company was licensed to broadcast digitally.
